
[1]mouse

   MOUSE, n. plu.mice. [L. mus; The L. mus forms muris in the genitive,
   and the root is not obvious.]

   1. A small animal of the genus Mus, inhabiting houses. The name is also
   applied to many other species of the genus, as the field mouse, meadow
   mouse, rock mouse, &c.

   2. Among seamen, a knob formed on a rope by spun yarn or parceling.

                      MOUSE, v.i.. mouz. To catch mice.

            MOUSE, v.t. mouz. To tear, as a cat devours a mouse.

     To mouse a hook, with seamen, is to fasten a small line across the
                      upper part to prevent unhooking.
